# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: paint-timing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] The temporal sensitivity and resolution of human vision vary depending on the type and characteristics of the visual stimulus, and it differs between individuals.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] The human visual system can process 10 to 12 images per second and perceive them individually, while higher rates are perceived as motion.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Modulated light (such as a computer display) is perceived as stable by the majority of participants in studies when the rate is higher than 50 FPS.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] This perception of modulated light as steady is known as the flicker fusion threshold.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] However, when the modulated light is non-uniform and contains an image, the flicker fusion threshold can be much higher, in the hundreds of hertz.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] With regard to image recognition, people have been found to recognize a specific image in an unbroken series of different images, each of which lasts as little as 13 milliseconds.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Persistence of vision sometimes accounts for very short single-millisecond visual stimulus having a perceived duration of between 100 ms and 400 ms.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Multiple stimuli that are very short are sometimes perceived as a single stimulus, such as a 10 ms green flash of light immediately followed by a 10 ms red flash of light perceived as a single yellow flash of light.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Early silent films had stated frame rates anywhere from 16 to 24 frames per second (FPS), but since the cameras were hand-cranked, the rate often changed during the scene to fit the mood.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Projectionists could also change the frame rate in the theater by adjusting a rheostat controlling the voltage powering the film-carrying mechanism in the projector.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Film companies often intended for theaters to show their silent films at a higher frame rate than that at which they were filmed.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] These frame rates were enough for the sense of motion, but it was perceived as jerky motion.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] To minimize the perceived flicker, projectors employed dual- and triple-blade shutters, so each frame was displayed two or three times, increasing the flicker rate to 48 or 72 FPS and reducing eye strain.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Thomas Edison said that 46 frames per second was the minimum needed for the eye to perceive motion: "Anything less will strain the eye." In the mid to late 1920s, the frame rate for silent film increased to 20–26 FPS.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] When sound film was introduced in 1926, variations in film speed were no longer tolerated, as the human ear is more sensitive than the eye to changes in frequency.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Many theaters had shown silent films at 22 to 26 FPS, which is why the industry chose 24 FPS for sound film as a compromise.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] From 1927 to 1930, as various studios updated equipment, the rate of 24 FPS became standard for 35 mm sound film.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] At 24 FPS, the film travels through the projector at a rate of 456 millimetres (18.0 in) per second.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] This allowed simple two-blade shutters to give a projected series of images at 48 per second, satisfying Edison's recommendation.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Many modern 35 mm film projectors use three-blade shutters to give 72 images per second—each frame is flashed on screen three times.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] In drawn animation, moving characters are often animated *on twos*, meaning one drawing is displayed for every two frames of film.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Since film typically runs at 24 frames per second, this results in a display of only 12 drawings per second.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Even though the image update rate is low, the fluidity is satisfactory for most subjects.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] However, when a character is required to perform a quick movement, it is usually necessary to revert to animating *on ones*, as *twos* are too slow to convey the motion adequately.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] A blend of the two techniques keeps the eye fooled and controls production cost.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Animation for most Saturday morning cartoons, first introduced in the mid-1960s, was produced as cheaply as possible and was most often shot on *threes* or even *fours*, i.e., three or four frames per drawing.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] This translates to only 8 or 6 drawings per second, respectively.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Anime is also usually drawn on threes or twos.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Due to the mains frequency of electric grids, analog television broadcast was developed with frame rates of 50 FPS (most of the world) or 60 FPS (Canada, US, Mexico, Philippines, Japan, South Korea).
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] The frequency of the electricity grid was extremely stable and therefore it was logical to use for synchronization.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] The introduction of color television technology made it necessary to lower that 60 FPS frequency by 0.1% to avoid "dot crawl", a display artifact appearing on legacy black-and-white displays, showing up on highly color-saturated surfaces.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] It was found that by lowering the frame rate by 0.1%, the undesirable effect was minimized.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] As of 2025, video transmission standards in North America, Japan, and South Korea are still based on 60/1.001 ≈ 59.94 images per second.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Confusingly, *interlaced* formats are customarily stated at half their image rate, 29.97/25 FPS, and *double* their image height, but these statements are purely custom; in each format, 60 images per second are produced.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] A resolution of 1080i produces 59.94 or 50 1920 × 540 images, each squashed to half-height in the photographic process and stretched back to fill the screen on playback in a television set.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] The 720p format produces 59.94/50 or 29.97/25 1280 × 720 images, not squeezed, so that no expansion or squeezing of the image is necessary.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] This confusion was industry-wide in the early days of digital video software, with much software being written incorrectly, the developers believing that only 29.97 images were expected each second.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] While it was true that each picture element was polled and sent only 29.97 times per second, the pixel location immediately below that one was polled 1/60 of a second later, part of a completely separate image for the next 1/60-second frame.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] At its native 24 FPS rate, film could not be displayed on 60 FPS video without the necessary pulldown process, often leading to *judder*: to convert 24 frames per second into 60 frames per second, every odd frame is repeated, playing twice, while every even frame is tripled.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] This creates uneven motion, appearing stroboscopic.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Other conversions have similar uneven frame doubling.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Newer video standards support 120, 240, or 300 frames per second, so frames can be evenly sampled for standard frame rates such as 24, 48 and 60 FPS film or 25, 30, 50 or 60 FPS video.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Of course these higher frame rates may also be displayed at their native rates.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] In computer video games, frame rate plays an important part in the experience as, unlike film, games are rendered in real-time.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] 60 frames per second has for a long time been considered the minimum frame rate for smoothly animated game play.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Video games designed for PAL markets, before the sixth generation of video game consoles, had lower frame rates by design due to the 50 Hz output.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] This noticeably made fast-paced games, such as racing or fighting games, run slower; less frequently developers accounted for the frame rate difference and altered the game code to achieve (nearly) identical pacing across both regions, with varying degrees of success.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Computer monitors marketed to competitive PC gamers can hit 360, 500 FPS, or more.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] High frame rates make action scenes look less blurry, such as sprinting through the wilderness in an open world game, spinning rapidly to face an opponent in a first-person shooter, or keeping track of details during an intense fight in a multiplayer online battle arena.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Some people may have difficulty perceiving the differences between high frame rates, though.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Frame time is related to frame rate, but it measures the time between frames.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] A game could maintain an average of 60 frames per second but appear choppy because of a poor frame time.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Game reviews sometimes average the worst 1% of frame rates, reported as the 99th percentile, to measure how choppy the game appears.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] A small difference between the average frame rate and 99th percentile would generally indicate a smooth experience.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] To mitigate the choppiness of poorly optimized games, players can set frame rate caps closer to their 99% percentile.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] When a game's frame rate is different from the display's refresh rate, screen tearing can occur.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Vsync mitigates this, but it caps the frame rate to the display's refresh rate, increases input lag, and introduces judder.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Variable refresh rate displays automatically set their refresh rate equal to the game's frame rate, as long as it is within the display's supported range.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Frame rate up-conversion (FRC) is the process of increasing the temporal resolution of a video sequence by synthesizing one or more intermediate frames between two consecutive frames.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] A low frame rate causes aliasing, yields abrupt motion artifacts, and degrades the video quality.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Consequently, the temporal resolution is an important factor affecting video quality.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Algorithms for FRC are widely used in applications, including visual quality enhancement, video compression and slow-motion video generation.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Most FRC methods can be categorized into optical flow or kernel-based and pixel hallucination-based methods.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Flow-based methods linearly combine predicted optical flows between two input frames to approximate flows from the target intermediate frame to the input frames.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] They also propose flow reversal (projection) for more accurate image warping.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Moreover, there are algorithms that give different weights of overlapped flow vectors depending on the object depth of the scene via a flow projection layer.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] Pixel hallucination-based methods use deformable convolution to the center frame generator by replacing optical flows with offset vectors.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] There are algorithms that also interpolate middle frames with the help of deformable convolution in the feature domain.
[src:paint-timing/frame-rate] However, since these methods directly hallucinate pixels, unlike the flow-based FRC methods, the predicted frames tend to be blurry when fast-moving objects are present.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Since December 2025, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The `LargestContentfulPaint` interface provides timing information about the largest image or text paint before user input on a web page.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The key moment this API provides is the Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) metric.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] It provides the render time of the largest image or text block visible within the viewport, recorded from when the page first begins to load.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] To measure render times of other elements, use the `PerformanceElementTiming` API.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] `LargestContentfulPaint` inherits from `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] To get an accurate measurement of render time for cross-origin resources, set the `Timing-Allow-Origin` header.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] See Cross-origin image render time and Use startTime over renderTime for more details.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The element that is the current largest contentful paint.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The time the element was rendered to the screen.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] May be a coarsened value if the element is a cross-origin image loaded without the `Timing-Allow-Origin` header.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The intrinsic size of the element returned as the area (width * height).
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] This property returns an empty string when there is no id.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Returns the `timestamp` when the rendering phase ended and the paint phase started.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Returns the `timestamp` when the painted pixels were actually drawn on the screen.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] If the element is an image, the request url of the image.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Returns the value of this entry's `renderTime`.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Returns `0`, as `duration` is not applicable to this interface.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Returns a JSON representation of the `LargestContentfulPaint` object.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] In the following example, a `PerformanceObserver` is registered to get the largest contentful paint while the page is loading.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The `buffered` flag is used to access data from before observer creation.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The LCP API analyzes all content it finds (including content that is removed from the DOM).
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] When new largest content is found, it creates a new entry.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] It stops searching for larger content when scroll or input events occur, since these events likely introduce new content on the website.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] Thus the LCP is the last performance entry reported by the observer.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The `paintTime` and `presentationTime` properties enable you to retrieve specific timings for the paint phase starting and the painted pixels being drawn on the screen.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] The `paintTime` is broadly interoperable, whereas the `presentationTime` is implementation-dependent.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] This example builds on the earlier observer example, showing how to check for `paintTime` and `presentationTime` support and retrieve those values if they are available.
[src:paint-timing/largestcontentfulpaint] In non-supporting browsers, the code retrieves the `renderTime` or `loadTime`, depending on what is supported.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] The Performance API is a group of standards used to measure the performance of web applications.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] To ensure web applications are fast, it's important to measure and analyze various performance metrics.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] The Performance API provides important built-in metrics and the ability to add your own measurements to the browser's performance timeline.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] The performance timeline contains high precision timestamps and can be displayed in developer tools.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] You can also send its data to analytics end points to record performance metrics over time.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Each performance metric is represented by a single `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] A performance entry has a `name`, a `duration`, a `startTime`, and a `type`.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] All performance metrics extend the `PerformanceEntry` interface and qualify it further.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Most of the performance entries are recorded for you without you having to do anything, and are then accessible either through `Performance.getEntries()` or (preferably) through `PerformanceObserver`.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] For example, `PerformanceEventTiming` entries are recorded for events that take longer than a set threshold.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] But the Performance API also enables you to define and record your own custom events, using the `PerformanceMark` and `PerformanceMeasure` interfaces.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] The main `Performance` interface is available in both `Window` and `Worker` global scopes, and enables you to add custom performance entries, to clear performance entries, and to retrieve performance entries.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] The `PerformanceObserver` interface enables you to listen for various types of performance entry as they are recorded.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] For more conceptual information, see the Performance API guides below.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] A read-only map returned by `performance.eventCounts` containing the number of events which have been dispatched per event type.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures the render time of the largest image or text block visible within the viewport, recorded from when the page first begins to load.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Provides insights into the layout stability of web pages based on movements of the elements on the page.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Provides debugging information about elements which have shifted.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Represents a single reason why a navigated page was blocked from using the back/forward cache (bfcache).
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Provides report data containing reasons why the current document was blocked from using the back/forward cache (bfcache) on navigation.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Main interface to access performance measurements.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Available to window and worker contexts using `Window.performance` or `WorkerGlobalScope.performance`.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures rendering timestamps of specific elements.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] An entry on the performance timeline encapsulating a single performance metric.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] All performance metrics inherit from this interface.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures latency of events and Interaction to Next Paint (INP).
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Provides metrics on long animation frames (LoAFs) that occupy rendering and block other tasks from being executed.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Provides metrics on long tasks that occupy rendering and block other tasks from being executed.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Custom marker for your own entry on the performance timeline.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Custom time measurement between two performance entries.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures document navigation events, like how much time it takes to load a document.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Listens for new performance entries as they are recorded in the performance timeline.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] List of entries that were observed in a performance observer.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures render operations during web page construction.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures network loading metrics such as redirect start and end times, fetch start, DNS lookup start and end times, response start and end times for resources such as images, scripts, fetch calls, etc.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Provides metrics on individual scripts causing long animation frames (LoAFs).
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Surfaces server metrics that are sent with the response in the `Server-Timing` HTTP header.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Identifies the type of task and the container that is responsible for the long task.
[src:paint-timing/performance-api] Measures the timing of page visibility state changes, i.e., when a tab changes from the foreground to the background or vice versa.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The read-only **`entryType`** property returns a string representing the type of performance metric that this entry represents.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] All supported `entryTypes` are available using the static property `PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes`.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The return value depends on the subtype of the `PerformanceEntry` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Some subtypes have more than one `entryType`.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceElementTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceEventTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports the largest paint an element triggered on screen.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `LargestContentfulPaint` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports layout stability of web pages based on movements of the elements on the page.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `LayoutShift` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports instances of long animation frames (LoAFs).
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceLongAnimationFrameTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceLongTaskTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports your own custom performance markers.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceMark` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports your own custom performance measures.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceMeasure` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports key moments of document rendering (first paint, first contentful paint) during page load.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformancePaintTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports timing information for resources in a document.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `PerformanceResourceTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports the type of work that contributed significantly to the long task.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `TaskAttributionTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Reports the timing of page visibility state changes, i.e., when a tab changes from the foreground to the background or vice versa.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The entry instance will be a `VisibilityStateEntry` object.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] The `entryType` property can be useful when filtering out specific performance entries.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] For example, you might want to check all script resources, so you would check for an `entryType` of `"resource"` and an `initiatorType` of `"script"`.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Both, `Performance` and `PerformanceObserver`, provide methods that allow you to get performance entries by type directly.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] You don't necessarily need the `entryType` property for that, instead you might use `Performance.getEntriesByType()` or `PerformanceObserverEntryList.getEntriesByType()`.
[src:paint-timing/performanceentry-entrytype] Also, when observing with a `PerformanceObserver`, the `observe()` method takes an array of `entryTypes` in its options object where you can decide which entry types to observe.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] The **`PerformancePaintTiming`** interface provides timing information about "paint" (also called "render") operations during web page construction.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] "Paint" refers to conversion of the render tree to on-screen pixels.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] The data this API provides helps you minimize the time that users have to wait before they can see the site's content start to appear.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Decreasing the time until these key paint moments make sites feel more responsive, performant, and engaging for your users.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Like other Performance APIs, this API extends `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Returns either `"first-paint"` or `"first-contentful-paint"`.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Returns the `timestamp` when the paint occurred.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformancePaintTiming` object.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Example using a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies of new `paint` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] Use the `buffered` option to access entries from before the observer creation.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] This example builds on the earlier `Performance.getEntriesByType()` example, showing how to check for `paintTime` and `presentationTime` support and retrieve those values if they are available.
[src:paint-timing/performancepainttiming] In non-supporting browsers, the code retrieves the `loadTime`.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:paint-timing/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
